# Types and interfaces

- Prefer `interface` for object shapes that may be extended or merged; use `type` for unions, intersections, mapped types, and utility compositions. Prefer using type over intefrace.
- Export types used across modules; keep internal-only types unexported when they are implementation details.
- Name types in PascalCase (`UserRow`, `CreatePostInput`). Avoid prefixing with `I` (e.g. not `IUser`).
- Prefer `unknown` over `any` at boundaries; narrow before use.
- If types or interfaces are used in more than one file, place them in folder @types. Check if there is suitable already existing file to place types and interfaces, if there is non, create new file with appropriate name.

```ts
// Prefer
type Result = { ok: true; data: string } | { ok: false; error: string };

// Avoid
const x: any = JSON.parse(raw);
```
